post_text: Thank you Scott for all of your help!
shared_text:
Scott Yaikow
June 23 at 3:41 PM Â·

I would like to take a few minutes to say thank you to our school system. I have had the privilege of preparing breakfast and lunches and then passing them out to the children and teenagers of Wilkes County for the last few months. During this time the work has been long and at times very hot. There has not been a time that I have heard anyone complain about having to do it or who was getting it. There were teachers, administrators, Board office employees, coaches, bus drivers and nutrition workers all present. They just wanted to make sure that all the students had food and felt the love that they had for them. It was incredible to watch and even more amazing to be a part of. Thank you for all that you have done for the children of Wilkes County, especially mine. I pray that God will shower His blessings on you and on your families.

post_text:
Do you know when to STOP for school buses?
Please help keep our students safe!

STOP: Itâ€™s the Law
Operation Stop Arm enforces Georgiaâ€™s School Bus Stop Law:
Â§ Two-lane roadway: When school bus stops for passengers, ALL traffic from both directions must stop.
Â§ Two-lane roadway with a center turning lane: When school bus stops for passengers, ALL traffic from both directions must stop.
Â§ Four-lane roadway without a median separation: When school bus stops for passengers, ALL traffic from both directions must stop.
Â§ Roadway of four lanes or more with a center turning lane: When school bus stops for passengers, ALL traffic from both directions must stop.
Â§ Divided highway of four lanes or more with a median separation: When school bus stops for passengers, only traffic following the bus must stop.

post_text:
We have several students at all schools who have the flu. However, our total absences (flu, non-flu, and all other absences) are still only around 10% systemwide. Because it is cold/flu season, we are taking extra precautions to combat the spread of germs. If your child is running a fever, please do not send them to school. Children and adults should be fever-free (without medication) for 24 hours before returning to school.
Please take some time to help us by reminding your child to wash their hands, cover their coughs and sneezes with their elbow or a tissue they can throw away, and use hand sanitizer.
We will continue to monitor absences and work with our local health department as well as utilize all DCH and CDC expertise and recommendations for safety at school.

The continuing threat of high winds, chance of flash floods, and downed trees and power lines make it too dangerous to travel. Please remain alert to changes in the weather and take all safety precautions! Our most dangerous time of the storm should begin around 8:00 pm tonight. Stay safe!

post_text:
Wilkes County Schools will be closed Monday, September 11. There will be no school activities on Monday. The threat of high winds, tornadoes, and heavy rain combined with the unpredictability of this storm could present dangerous situations that threaten the safety of our students, staff, and parents particularly while traveling to and from school.
We will continue to monitor conditions before making a decision about Tuesday. Any further announcements will be made through local radio/tv, Facebook, and our OneCallNow notification system.
Please remain alert to changing conditions and safety precautions.
Please share!

post_text: Students in Wilkes County Schools will enjoy the eclipse inside the building today. The glasses we ordered in anticipation of the event were not on the official "approved" list, so we are watching the livestream of the eclipse in classrooms. Even though we are unable to provide safe solar viewing, students will be able to see the darkening of the skies through their classroom window and experience the total eclipse via livestream.
